feedback-fq1:
For shortest path questions, I hovered over both of the target nodes and tried to eyeball which adjacent nodes were most likely to be on the shortest path. This worked pretty well when the path was short but was less reliable for longer ones.

For counting the number of neighbors with a given degree, I hovered over the target node then swept my eyes in a circle around each neighbor. If it was ambiguous (e.g. because of overlapping edges) I would double check by hovering on the neighbor.
feedback-fq2: There were two main challenges. On every visualization style, edges sometimes overlapped visually which made it necessary to rely on the hover tool to figure out what was going on. And specifically on the last style, the fisheye effect made it difficult to have both highlighted nodes clearly in view, which made finding a shortest path more difficult.
feedback-fq4: The last style was visually fun, but less intuitive than the globe and the plane. I guess the main advantage would be automatically magnifying the focused node, but I feel like the effect was too strong here, making it hard to look at the whole graph all at once.
